</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1209</anchor>  <taxon>Theorem</taxon> <addr>axt-0045</addr>  <route>axt-0045.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>21</day></date> <authors><author><link href="brian-davey.xml" type="local">Brian A. Davey</link></author><author><link href="hilary-priestley.xml" type="local">Hilary Ann Priestley</link></author> </authors> <title>Knaster-Tarski fixed point theorem</title> <meta name="source"><b>Defn 2.35</b> of <link href="davey-priestley-book.xml" type="local" title="Introduction to Lattices and Order">Davey and Priestley</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Let <tex>L</tex> be a complete lattice and <tex>F : L  \to  L</tex> a monotone map.
  Then the set
  <tex display="block">\alpha   \vcentcolon \equiv   \bigvee   \left \{  x  \in  L  \mid  x  \le  F(x)  \right \}</tex>  is a fixed point of <tex>F</tex>.
</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>We first define the abbreviation <tex>H   \vcentcolon \equiv   \{   x   \in  L  \mid   x   \le  F( x )  \}</tex>.</p>  <p>    To show <tex>F( \alpha ) =  \alpha</tex>, we use antisymmetry. For the <tex>( \ge )</tex>    direction, it suffices to show <tex>F( \alpha )</tex> is an upper bound of <tex>H</tex>.
    Let <tex>x  \in  H</tex>. We know <tex>x  \le   \alpha</tex> as <tex>\alpha</tex> is the least upper
    bound of <tex>H</tex> which implies <tex>F(x)  \le  F( \alpha )</tex>. We also know <tex>x  \le  F(x)</tex>    by the definition of <tex>H</tex> which means <tex>x  \le  F(x)  \le  F( \alpha )</tex>.
    For the <tex>( \le )</tex> direction, notice that we know <tex>F( \alpha )  \le     F(F( \alpha ))</tex> by the fact we just showed which means <tex>F( \alpha )  \in  H</tex>.
    It follows that <tex>F( \alpha )  \le   \alpha</tex> since <tex>\alpha</tex> is the least upper
    bound of <tex>H</tex>.
  </p></block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1210</anchor>  <taxon>Axiom</taxon> <addr>axt-003A</addr>  <route>axt-003A.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>6</day></date> <authors><author><link href="hilary-priestley.xml" type="local">Hilary Ann Priestley</link></author> </authors> <title>Alternative formulation of Zornâ€™s Lemma</title> <meta name="source"><tex>(ZL)''</tex> from <link href="davey-priestley-book.xml" type="local" title="Introduction to Lattices and Order">Davey and Priestley</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Every <link href="axt-003B.xml" type="local" title="Pointed dcpo">pointed dcpo</link> has a <link href="axt-0039.xml" type="local" title="Maximal element">maximal element</link>.
</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1211</anchor>  <taxon>Axiom</taxon> <addr>axt-003D</addr>  <route>axt-003D.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>6</day></date> <authors><author><link href="brian-davey.xml" type="local">Brian A. Davey</link></author><author><link href="hilary-priestley.xml" type="local">Hilary Ann Priestley</link></author> </authors> <title>Axiom of choice in set theory</title> <meta name="source"><b>Paragraph 10.1</b> of <link href="davey-priestley-book.xml" type="local" title="Introduction to Lattices and Order">Davey and Priestley</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  For every nonempty family <tex>\{  A_i  \} _{i  \in  I}</tex> of nonempty sets, there
  exists a function <tex>f : I  \to   \bigcup _{i  \in  I} A_i</tex> such that
  <tex display="block">\forall  i  \in  I. \  f(i)  \in  A_i.</tex></p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1212</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-003G</addr>  <route>axt-003G.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>6</day></date> <authors><author><link href="brian-davey.xml" type="local">Brian A. Davey</link></author><author><link href="hilary-priestley.xml" type="local">Hilary Ann Priestley</link></author> </authors> <title>Fixed point</title> <meta name="source"><b>Defn. 8.14</b> of <link href="davey-priestley-book.xml" type="local" title="Introduction to Lattices and Order">Davey and Priestley</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Let <tex>P</tex> be a partially ordered set and let <tex>h : P  \to  P</tex> be an endofunction.
  An element <tex>x  \in  P</tex> is called a <b>fixed point</b> of <tex>h</tex> if it
  satisfies <tex>h(x) = x</tex>.
</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1213</anchor>   <addr>axt-003H</addr>  <route>axt-003H.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>6</day></date> <authors><author><link href="brian-davey.xml" type="local">Brian A. Davey</link></author><author><link href="hilary-priestley.xml" type="local">Hilary Ann Priestley</link></author> </authors> <title>Least fixed point</title> <meta name="source"><b>Defn. 8.14</b> of <link href="davey-priestley-book.xml" type="local" title="Introduction to Lattices and Order">Davey and Priestley</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Let <tex>P</tex> be a partially ordered set and let <tex>h : P  \to  P</tex> be an endofunction.
  An element <tex>x  \in  P</tex> is called the <b>least fixed point</b> of <tex>h</tex> if
  <ul>    <li>it is a <link href="axt-003G.xml" type="local" title="Fixed point">fixed point</link> of <tex>h</tex>, and</li>    <li>it is below any other fixed point of <tex>h</tex>.</li>  </ul>  When it exists, the least fixed point is denoted <tex>\mu ( h )</tex>.
</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>